          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">The WWII code-breaker died
        </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/ms-webb-mbe-award-2015-honor-recognition.png" alt="Ms Webb was made an MBE in 2015" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Ms Webb was made an MBE in 2015. Credits: The Independent</i></p>
        </mj-text>
      
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Women's Royal Army Corps Association (WRAC) reported that <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-03-04-2025-h2-3-charlotte-betty-web?source=website" target="_blank">Charlotte "Betty" Webb</a> MBE, the UK’s oldest surviving WWII code-breaker, passed away at the age of 101. Hailing from the village of Wythall, just south of Birmingham, Webb started her work as a secretary. However, when people started noticing her skills in registering messages, she was asked to commit to the Official Secret Act and index 10,000 messages daily.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">She played a vital role in deciphering German communications during the war and later contributed to Japanese code-breaking at the Pentagon in the US. Webb did not reveal her nature of work until 1975. Her book, <i>No More Secrets: My Part in Codebreaking at Bletchley Park and the Pentagon</i>, chronicled her life at Bletchley Park and became the subject of the 2014 movie <i><a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-03-04-2025-h2-4-the-imitation-game?source=website" target="_blank">The Imitation Game</a></i>. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Her life and work have inspired many and garnered many accolades. In 2015, she was made a Member of the Order of the British Empire (MBE), and France honored her with the highest distinction, the Legion d'Honneur, in recognition of her service. In 2023, she celebrated her 100th birthday at Bletchley, where a Lancaster bomber performed a fly-past in her honor. She was also invited to attend King Charles III’s coronation.</p>
        </mj-text>
